  "market_context": "NQ daily chart trading within a range. Over the prior three days, multiple previous day lows remain untaken (failure swings), while on the high end a recent day swept a prior day's high creating high resistance liquidity above.",
  "key_observation": "When previous day lows form failure swings (low resistance liquidity) while previous day highs already swept each other (high resistance liquidity), the bias favors a draw lower to sweep the stacked, easy-to-take lows.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identify that the last three daily candles left multiple previous day lows untouched, marking them as failure swings / low resistance liquidity.",
    "Look at the high side and note that a recent day already took out the prior day's high, creating high resistance liquidity above.",
    "Drop to the hourly chart to confirm: price swept one side of the range (high), creating high resistance liquidity, with failure swing lows resting below.",
    "Anticipate a retrace back into the range followed by an expansion lower to take out the stacked low resistance liquidity.",
    "Confirm on a second NQ daily example: sweep and closure back inside range on the lows forms high resistance liquidity, while failure swings sit on the highs — bias flips to long, and price runs the highs.",
    "Use the symmetry of high resistance vs failure swings on each side of the daily range to add conviction to directional bias."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price retraced into the range and then expanded down to take out the low resistance liquidity below the previous day lows, as anticipated.",
  "lessons": "On the daily chart, locate where failure swings (low resistance liquidity) and high resistance liquidity sit on each side of the range. Price gravitates toward the failure-swing side, so this asymmetry is a powerful bias filter.",
